review_blob: sweet honey low bitterness gold out of a clear blottle. very generic flavour.
nice golden color, with a decent head. perfectly balanced rich malty flavour and medium bitterness. a real surprise, but it was excellent.
a deep red colour and tan head, slightly burnt toffee flavour, sweet and fruity and obviously warms you up nicely.
worse than i thought. has that taste familiar to all cub beer. watery and grassy tasting, with the typical sickly sweetness that a lot of low/alc beer has.

a little bit dissapointing for me. i was expecting it to be more like urquell. very drinkable though and much better than the equivilant priced imports. very balanced flavour, no so bitter, and light malt flavour.

just another cheap australian lager, with the typical chemical flavours, but this ones a little sweeter than most and slightly above average. just been released in WA with the usual advertising campaign. no more VB for me.
mine was brewed in new zealand and was a piss weak yellow, with a fizzy head. fairly low on flavour. tastred a bit metallic, just another generic lager.
the closest to gold in colour i have ever seen in a beer. no head but. like little creatures, but lighter on the hops and more malt and caramel flavour.
beer_name: James Squire The Chancer Golden Ale

review_blob: quite cloudy, tastes and smells to much like honey. too fizzy. a bit thin and bland.
massive off white head and a red brown colour. tastes of grape, molasses, citrus and alcohol. Very thick and sweet. cant have more than one at a time.
a very standard tasting bitter, with nothing remarkable about it, but is very good. very clean tasting and very floral.
beer_name: Samuel Smiths Organic Best Ale / Organically Produced Ale

review_blob: quite watery, brown colour, no head. standard flavour and little bitterness.

very thick and chewy. strong burnt flavour and bitterness, with the usual chocolate, coffee, malty taste. dark brown head, very black and opaque with some floaties. you can start to taste the alcohol towards the end.
excellent, nice and malty and prominent bitterness. hint of honey flavour. Gold and slightly cloudy with a small head.
a golden colour, little head flavours and bitterness very well balanced. clean tasting lager.
Nothing remarkable, odd smell, no head and is not highly hopped. dissapointing
Standard golden/red colour, with no head. Grapefruit/passionfruit hop flavour well balanced with a malty taste.
no head, very deep red/brown colour. Not an IPA at 3.6%. Why is this given two different style names. not much in the way of hop character, and a bit watery.
very cheap, and at least its in a brown bottle. doesnt taste to bad for a cheapo lager. goes flat very fast, and is a bit sweet. to call it a pilsner though is ridiculous. just another pale lager.
its quite a good cheapo. easy drinking, with minimal malt or hops. does smell a bit CUB.
standard pale lager. a bit weak and watery. a bit corny and malty with little bitterness. tastes like an asian lager.
not to bad. a bit watery, but better than I expected. is everybody sure this is a pale lager?

dissapointing. the honey flavour stands out but is not overpowering. as far as this being a wheat beer, you wouldnt know by the flavour. it tastes like fosters with a bit of honey in it. CUB cant do anything right.
a pale lager with a light hop finish, and a slightly sweet malty flavor. yep its beer and its french and its crap.

this is not what i expected but i liked it. the person who said it has something vaguely reminiscent of VB is spot on, though ill be less insulting and say it is quite ciderish. not as malty or "thick" as most of the same style, though as it warms it gets sweeter and the aroma maltier.
came in a very big fancy looking can(thats why I bought it). nothing can really be said of this beer other than that it is a very standard pale lager. better than most standard pale lagers however.

passionfruit and caramel aroma. golden brown and almost red colour, with a slightly off white head. same flavours as the aroma, plus the tinyist smokey flavour. the perfect beer. everything is well balanced.
orange with a big white head. better than your average of the style. fulfilling flavour.

rich dark colour, and a very small creamy brown head. smells a tiny bit smokey, and chocolatey. a quite fruity grape flavour, and of course there is the standard coffee and ckhocolate flavour. not as roasty as most stouts, and almost chewable. excellent.
deep copper colour, with averagre white head. malty and bitter. caramel flavour not overpowering.
tasted very ordinary. nothing stands out with this. closest beer, might be CUB's Bohemian Pilzner.
nice copper colour. almost pinkish. big off-white head. great fruity taste, grapefruity, and bitter.
it is like corona. same bottle, same yellow fizzy water. not much else to say.

440mL can. the nitro widget in this seemed to make the head frothier than most other widgert cans, and it spills over the top every time.
big frothy dead white head, orange brown colour, and the usual caramel, and malt tastes from a macro bitter.
a magnificent, sweet roasty/malty, beer, with a large white head and a deep, dark, red colour. you don't get much better than this.
ruby bronze. little head. typical aroma. caramel and typical bitter flavours. burnt bitter after taste. very good.
excellent, dark brown and red. very sweet with raisin aroma. can taste the alcohol a bit, but very easy drinking, malty and syrupy.
quite dissapointing. you can taste the carlton and United influence. a bit too much like fosters, but with a little more malt and hop flavour and bitterness.

made only for queensland, but managed to find this in one liquor store in Perth(not that i was looking for it). open the can and you immediatly get an aroma of shit. it is a dark amber colour. darker than most of these crappy cub lagers. has a distinctive corn sweetness, and is very light on the cub, skunk. quite watery. better than i expected.
mine was about 4 years out of date. i think it improved it. it tasted and smelled just like honey. i couldn't taste the alcohol at all. a lot like carlsberg lager i guess.
a lot like Matilda Bay Pilsner. bitter bite, and very fruity and floral. no malt, and is a nice pale colour.
lightly cloudy orange appearance. smells a bit like leather. typical banana, clove, orange etc. quite thin.

finally got round to trying it and I reckon it is the best of the range. nice dark copper colour. a tiny bit of roasted malt flavour but mainly a sweet malty taste. it is quite thin, and has a slightly lagerish after taste. great.
beer_name: James Squire Nine Tales Amber Ale

review_blob: UPDATED: NOV 19, 2003

i am starting to become less and less interested in nitro beer. this is quite good, a bit thin and watery, which you expect from a nitro beer. usual flavours for a bitter. good for when you are bored of the macro lager at the pub.

quite dark with biege, fast dissipating head. coffee is the dominant flavour, and this beer is really quite thin. plenty of sweet flavours, a bit of caramel and chocolate etc. roasty and sweet aftertaste. a must try.
big fluffy white head and quite pale in colour. the usual kristall weizen flavours and aromas.  really quite fruity, and definitely one to try again.
an aroma of caramel and sea water. deep copper colour, with an off white creamy head. this is bitter-sweet. slightly roasty, and very caramelly. pretty sweet.

dark black with brown edges and a biege creamy head. smooth pour. has a velvety chocolate feel and flavour in the mouth. subtle roastiness for a stout. very smooth. the aroma at the end in of sweet milk chocolate.
this is quite dark. very malty, slightly bitter, very enjoyable. could be called a chocolate lager.
